Anonymous Sun 11 Jun 2017 18:48:18 No.9839281 Report
Quoted By: >>9839497 >>9839749
>>9839012
So if you wanted to genetically engineer anthros how would you go about it?

Splicing genes isn't guaranteed to produce any sensible results at least with our current understanding of what does what in genetics.
Using the same method that was used to grow human organs inside pigs to grow an animal that's human from the neck down seems tempting but differing skeletal structure will cause serious problems with that idea.
Taking a human embryo and altering the expression of their genes to create pseudo furries wouldn't be as difficult as splicing but would still require far more knowledge about genetics and also comes with whole host of ethical issues.
Taking and animal embryo as base and getting it to express more human characteristics could be even easier depending on how humanoid you want the end result to be and would carry less ethical issues (hell ownership might even be plausible there) but would of course produce a fairly unintelligent anthro, though for some that might be a good thing.
